  "doc_id": "30220",
  "text": "Our objective was to better describe the relationship between H. galeatus population densities and bentgrass health using both visual and MSR indices and measurements of net photosynthetic rate (P n ). We also examined the influence of cultivar, clipping height, and irrigation frequency in association with H. galeatus populations on bentgrass quality on a naturally infested putting green. Population responses of H. galeatus to these experimental manipulations were reported separately [CITATION_1] . Briefly, H. galeatus population densities were spatially and temporally variable, but no consistent trends in the effects of turfgrass management practices were detected. Peak population densities occurred in late summer or early autumn and often coincided with periods of maximum turfgrass stress from environmental factors (e.g., temperature). Nematode numbers during these months consistently exceeded estimated threshold levels [CITATION_2] .",
